### Exhaustiveness Checking

Use mapped types and `keyof` to ensure all required keys are present. Combine with discriminated unions for exhaustive switch statements.

```typescript
type Status = 'idle' | 'loading' | 'success' | 'error';

// Exhaustive handler - must cover all states
type StatusHandler = {
  [K in Status]: (data: any) => void;
};

const handler: StatusHandler = {
  idle: () => console.log('idle'),
  loading: () => console.log('loading'),
  success: () => console.log('success'),
  error: () => console.log('error')
};
// ERROR if any status is missing

type Result<T> = { status: 'success'; data: T } | { status: 'error'; error: string };

const processResult = <T,>(result: Result<T>) => {
  switch (result.status) {
    case 'success':
      console.log(result.data); // T
      break;
    case 'error':
      console.log(result.error); // string
      break;
    default:
      const _exhaustive: never = result.status;
      return _exhaustive;
  }
};
```

Mapped types force completeness. The `never` assignment in `default` catches missing cases at compile-time.

**Common interview trap:** Candidates forget the `default: never` pattern or don't understand discriminated unions. Also, they might add properties without updating the mapped type, missing compile-time errors. Union narrowing in switch cases only works with literal types.

