### Template Literal Types

Template literal types allow constraining strings to specific patterns using union types and pattern matching. They enable type-safe APIs with dynamic string composition.

```typescript
type HttpMethod = 'GET' | 'POST' | 'PUT' | 'DELETE';
type ResourceName = 'users' | 'posts' | 'comments';
type RoutePattern = `/${ResourceName}` | `/${ResourceName}/:id`;

type Route = {
  path: RoutePattern;
  method: HttpMethod;
  handler: (req: any) => any;
};

const routes: Route[] = [
  { path: '/users', method: 'GET', handler: () => [] },
  { path: '/users/:id', method: 'GET', handler: () => {} },
  { path: '/posts', method: 'POST', handler: () => {} },
  { path: '/invalid', method: 'GET', handler: () => {} } // ERROR
];

type CSSUnit = `${number}px` | `${number}%` | `${number}em`;
const padding: CSSUnit = '16px'; // OK
const invalid: CSSUnit = '16'; // ERROR
```

Template literals combine string patterns with unions to enforce format constraints. Extract parts using conditional types and `infer`.

**Common interview trap:** Candidates forget that template literal types are still strings at runtime. They provide no validation; they only constrain the type system. Also, complex patterns require careful union decomposition to avoid type bloat.

