answer.en:
### Type-Safe Configuration System

Combine branded types with builders to create configurations that enforce both structure and validation rules at compile-time. Each step returns a more specific type, preventing incomplete or invalid configurations from being used.

This pattern uses type predicates and exhaustiveness checking to ensure only valid configurations reach runtime. The brand serves as proof that validation occurred.

```typescript
type Validated<T> = T & { readonly __validated: true };

interface ConfigInput {
  host: string;
  port: number;
  ssl: boolean;
}

type ValidConfig = Validated<ConfigInput>;

class ConfigBuilder {
  private config: Partial<ConfigInput> = {};

  setHost(h: string): this { this.config.host = h; return this; }
  setPort(p: number): this { this.config.port = p; return this; }
  setSSL(s: boolean): this { this.config.ssl = s; return this; }

  build(): ValidConfig {
    const required: (keyof ConfigInput)[] = ['host', 'port', 'ssl'];
    for (const key of required) {
      if (!(key in this.config)) throw new Error(`Missing ${key}`);
    }
    return this.config as ValidConfig;
  }
}

const config = new ConfigBuilder()
  .setHost('localhost')
  .setPort(3000)
  .setSSL(true)
  .build();
```


**Common interview trap:** Candidates create branded types but don't enforce that only validated configs are accepted in functions—the brand must be checked in function signatures.

