### Exhaustiveness Checking with Never

Assign unhandled union members to `never` in the `default` branch of a `switch`. TypeScript will flag this as a compile error if a union member can ever reach the default branch — i.e., if you missed a case.

```typescript
type Status =
  | { kind: 'pending' }
  | { kind: 'success'; value: number }
  | { kind: 'error'; message: string };

function describe(status: Status): string {
  switch (status.kind) {
    case 'pending':  return 'Waiting...';
    case 'success':  return `Value: ${status.value}`;
    case 'error':    return `Error: ${status.message}`;
    default: {
      // If you add { kind: 'cancelled' } to Status without a case here,
      // TypeScript errors: "Type 'never' has no construct signatures"
      const _exhaustive: never = status;
      return _exhaustive;
    }
  }
}

// Alternative: extract the helper to get a runtime guard too
function assertNever(x: never, msg = 'Unexpected value'): never {
  throw new Error(`${msg}: ${JSON.stringify(x)}`);
}

function describe2(status: Status): string {
  switch (status.kind) {
    case 'pending':  return 'Waiting...';
    case 'success':  return `Value: ${status.value}`;
    case 'error':    return `Error: ${status.message}`;
    default:         return assertNever(status); // compile + runtime guard
  }
}
```

**Common interview trap:** Thinking exhaustiveness checking works on binary unions with if/else. For a two-member union, after one branch handles `r.ok === true` the other `else` branch is already narrowed by exclusion — there is no reachable `never` default. The `switch + default: never` pattern is most valuable when the union has 3+ members and may grow over time.

