### Phantom Types for State Safety

Phantom types are generic parameters that don't appear in the runtime value but exist only for type checking. They enable compile-time enforcement of state machines and prevent invalid operations on incompletely initialized objects.

```typescript
type State = 'locked' | 'unlocked';
class Door<S extends State = 'locked'> {
  private state!: S;
  unlock(this: Door<'locked'>): Door<'unlocked'> { return this as Door<'unlocked'>; }
  open(this: Door<'unlocked'>): void { console.log('Opening'); }
}
const d = new Door().unlock().open(); // ✓ Type-safe
```

**Common interview trap:** Thinking phantom types require runtime overhead or that the generic parameter must be stored in the object.

